subSubSection.paragraph:
Number of subtaxa. 6 genera (3 subgenera in genus
Otostigmus
). “Ca 200 species in six genera” sensu Edgecombe & Bonato (2011: 400) .

Diagnosis.
Median tooth of labrum well developed (
Fig. 94
). Second article of telopodite of maxilla 2 with (in most species) or without dorsal distal spur; pretarsus with 1 or 2 (
Fig. 95
) accessory spines. Forcipular tooth-plates present, trochantero-prefemur with well-developed process (
Fig. 96
). In a few species tergites with longitudinal keels (fig. 
16 in
Schileyko & Stoev 2016
). Sternites with paramedian sutures (more rarely sulci) developed to varying degrees and, sometimes with median and paired lateral depressions. LBS 7 lacking spiracles, the latter in most species with deep atrium (
Fig. 82
). Legs with tarsal spur(s) in the overwhelming majority of species. Posterior margin of male ultimate tergite without elongated projection. Coxopleural process in most species well-developed (if so, it is oriented caudad; 
Fig. 93
), with apical (in most species plus lateral and sometimes plus dorsal) spines; in a few species coxopleural process much reduced (figs 
59, 60 in
Lewis 2014
). Prefemur of the ultimate leg with spines (
Fig. 83
) and with or without (more or less developed) corner spine, pretarsus well-developed.

